I can see where he might have enjoyed functional relationships, up to having been steady/engaged with a woman prior to discovering his infertility. If the two had spent the entirety of their relationship with the intent to start a family once meeting some condition (like buying a house), that revelation might shock them both. If protag' (the MC) is opposed to adopting or seeking a donor, that may strain their relationship, especially if their shared desire to raise a family factored into his waifur's attraction to him (which may include an intense, maternal desire to physically procreate, ruling out adoption). I guess it depends on how you summarize your narrative: If you lean towards "man and fuzzy/feathered fiance's unshakable love for one another in jeopardy over the revelation he may never be able to create the family they've always desired," then your story follows the near-collapse or failure of a relationship between two individuals who are deeply in love (with history; childhood romance for those hard-hitting feels), and how they do/don't survive that challenge. If it's about a man whose infertility severely handicaps his potential as a mate due to the value your fictional society places on being able to have children (a colonial/American frontier setting?), then you'd write about how he comes to accept it, or a situation under which his circumstances change, like meeting a woman that doesn't share those values.
